<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="579" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,419,649,674]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Head white, frons black with white hairs. Second joint of palpus white from outside, black from inside, third segment black. Antenna black, white-ringed with black club. Thorax and abdomen dark-brown on upperside, white on underside. Legs white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Wings upperside ochraceous-brown with violaceous suffusion extending from base to submarginal region, more intensive in basal region. Forewing with dark-brown spot near discoidal vein. Submarginal region dull ochraceous, most intensive near anal angle of hindwing, with black spots between veins in subcostal region and ochraceous suffusion along veins. Hindwing with thin silvery-blue line along edge of tornal region, bears rather long black tail with white tip. Outer margin of both wings with black edge.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
Wings underside dirty-white, with pattern of large extended black dots surrounded by white rings and spots. Submarginal orange band well-developed on both wings, rather broad, broader on forewing, inner edge of hindwing band with weak black suffusion. Subcostal region with black dots, rounded on forewing, strike-like on hindwing. Outer margin of both wings with black edge. Fringe black internally, white externally, with brown markings near veins. Forewing length 15,0 mm in the 
<typeStatus box="[758,859,1081,1106]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">holotype</typeStatus>
, 12,0–16,0 mm in the series of specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Male genitalia. Uncus well-developed, prominent. Falx long, thin, pointed, with tip slightly curved upwards. Saccus very short, triangle. Valva thin, long, with inner fold situated close to rounded distal end. Aedeagus long, crescent, gradually pointed to tip.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1223,1248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to male, but orange pattern of both wing surfaces more developed, especially on forewing upperside where band reaches transverse vein. Forewing length 13,0–15,0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,1294,1319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Individual variation.</emphasis>
Size and shape of spots on wings underside strongly varies from circles to thin strokes; extension of orange area on forewing upperside of females varies slightly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="579" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1365,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Poorly developed orange pattern along costal edge of wings upperside, silvery line on hindwing upperside, and reduced black spots on inner edge of orange submarginal band of hindwing underside are diagnostic characters of 
<taxonomicName box="[305,429,1436,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Athamanthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balucha">
<emphasis box="[305,429,1436,1460]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">A. balucha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
according to the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Howarth" box="[866,1163,1436,1461]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" refString="Howarth, T. G. &amp; Povolny, D. (1976) Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Fauna afghanistans. Casopis Moravskeho musea v Brne, 61, 139 - 170." type="journal article" year="1976">Howarth &amp; Povolny 1976</bibRefCitation>
) and photos of the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1437,1461]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">type</typeStatus>
specimens (
<bibRefCitation author="Nekrutenko" box="[282,483,1471,1496]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" refString="Nekrutenko, Yu. P. (1984) A revision of the type specimens of Lycaena phoenicurus group (Lepidoptera, Lycaenidae). Vestnik Zoologii, 6, 43 - 49. [in Russian with English summary]" type="journal article" year="1984">Nekrutenko 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bozano" box="[494,834,1471,1496]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" refString="Bozano, G. C. &amp; Weidenhoffer, Z. (2001) Guide to the Butterflies of the Palearctic Region. Lycaenidae part I. Lycaeninae. Omnes Artes, Milano, 62 pp." type="book" year="2001">Bozano &amp; Weidenhoffer 2001</bibRefCitation>
). These traits are shared with 
<emphasis box="[1168,1264,1472,1496]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">povolnyi</emphasis>
and specimens recently found in 
<collectingCountry box="[348,488,1507,1532]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
. The male genitalia are identical to those of the nominate subspecies. Compared with 
<taxonomicName authority="Lederer, 1871" authorityName="Lederer" authorityYear="1871" box="[151,508,1542,1567]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Lycaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phoenicurus">
<emphasis box="[151,322,1542,1566]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">A. phoenicurus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lederer" box="[337,499,1542,1567]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" refString="Lederer, J. (1871) Nachtrag zum Verzeichnisse der von Herrn Jos. Haberhauer bei Astrabad in Persien gesammelten Schmetterlinge. Horae Societatis Entomologicae Rossicae, 8, 8 - 9." type="journal article" year="1871">Lederer, 1871</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, they are characterized by broad uncus, extended valva with developed inner fold and less indented apex, slightly upturned stout saccus and crescent aedeagus. Taking into consideration these differences as well as disjunct distribution, we treat the taxon 
<emphasis box="[850,946,1614,1638]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">povolnyi</emphasis>
as a subspecies of 
<emphasis box="[1164,1314,1614,1638]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicName box="[1164,1286,1614,1638]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Athamanthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balucha">A. balucha</taxonomicName>
—
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Howarth &amp; Povolny, 1976" authorityName="Howarth &amp; Povolny" authorityYear="1976" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Athamanthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="balucha" status="comb. nov." subSpecies="povolnyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">A. balucha povolnyi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Howarth" box="[263,567,1649,1674]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" refString="Howarth, T. G. &amp; Povolny, D. (1976) Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Fauna afghanistans. Casopis Moravskeho musea v Brne, 61, 139 - 170." type="journal article" year="1976">Howarth &amp; Povolny, 1976</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[587,717,1649,1674]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[587,717,1649,1674]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
The diagnostic characters of the subspecies we found are more developed orange submarginal pattern on the hindwing upperside of both sexes and well developed orange area on the forewing upperside of female.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
